  "prompt": "What is the present Infant Mortality Rate (IMR) of Nepal? What is the government doing to improve it?",
  "response": "As of the most recent data available, the Infant Mortality Rate (IMR) in Nepal stands at approximately 27 deaths per 1,000 live births (as per the World Bank data for 2020). However, specific figures can vary slightly depending on the source and year of data.\n\nThe Government of Nepal has been actively working to improve the IMR through various initiatives and programs:\n\n1. **Maternal and Child Health Programs**: The government has prioritized maternal and child health through programs like the National Safe Motherhood Program and the Community-Based Newborn Care Program. These programs focus on improving access to skilled birth attendants, promoting antenatal care, and providing essential newborn care.\n\n2. **Immunization Campaigns**: Nepal has made significant strides in immunization coverage, which plays a crucial role in reducing infant mortality. The government conducts regular vaccination campaigns to ensure that children are protected against preventable diseases.\n\n3. **Nutrition Initiatives**: Malnutrition is a major contributor to infant mortality. Programs like the Multi-Sector Nutrition Plan aim to improve the nutritional status of mothers and children through interventions such as micronutrient supplementation, breastfeeding promotion, and community-based nutrition education.\n\n4. **Healthcare Infrastructure**: The government has been expanding healthcare facilities, particularly in rural areas, to ensure better access to medical services. Initiatives include the construction of birthing centers and the deployment of health workers to remote regions.\n\n5. **Health Education and Awareness**: Public health campaigns are regularly conducted to raise awareness about the importance of timely medical check-ups, vaccinations, and proper nutrition for infants and young children.\n\n6. **Partnerships with NGOs and International Organizations**: The government collaborates with non-governmental organizations (NGOs) and international bodies such as the World Health Organization (WHO) and UNICEF to leverage resources and expertise in improving child health outcomes.\n\nThese efforts collectively aim to reduce the IMR and improve overall child health in Nepal. However, challenges such as geographical barriers, socio-economic disparities, and limited resources continue to be areas of focus for further improvement.",
